    FPClassTest NoFPClass = CB->getParamNoFPClass(U.getOperandNo());
    DemandedMask &= ~NoFPClass;
  }
```
Wait! `VInst` is the instruction that *produces* the value `V`.
But `CB->getParamNoFPClass(U.getOperandNo())` gets the `nofpclass` attribute of the parameter of `CB` at index `U.getOperandNo()`.
Wait, `U.getOperandNo()` is the operand number of `I`, not `CB`!
If `VInst` is a `CallBase`, `U.getOperandNo()` is the operand number of `I` (the instruction being simplified).
This means it's getting the `nofpclass` attribute of the *producing* call instruction's parameter, using the operand index of the *consuming* instruction!
This is a huge bug!

Let's trace this carefully.
`I` is the instruction being simplified.
`OpNo` is the operand index of `I`.
`U` is `I->getOperandUse(OpNo)`.
`V` is `U.get()`.
`VInst` is `dyn_cast<Instruction>(V)`.
If `VInst` is a `CallBase` (i.e., `V` is the result of a call instruction), then:
```cpp
  if (const CallBase *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(VInst)) {
    FPClassTest NoFPClass = CB->getParamNoFPClass(U.getOperandNo());
    DemandedMask &= ~NoFPClass;
  }
```
It casts `VInst` to `CallBase *CB`.
Then it calls `CB->getParamNoFPClass(U.getOperandNo())`.
But `U.getOperandNo()` is `OpNo`, which is the operand index of `I`!
It has absolutely nothing to do with `CB`'s parameters!
This means if `I` is an instruction (e.g., `fadd`), and its operand `OpNo` is a call instruction `CB`, it will query `CB`'s parameter attribute at index `OpNo`.
But `CB`'s return value is what's being used. `CB`'s parameters are its arguments.
Why would it query `CB`'s parameter attribute?
Wait, the patch says:
"InstCombine: Apply parameter nofpclass in SimplifyDemandedFPClass
Apply the use operand's nofpclass to the demanded mask."
If the intention was to apply the `nofpclass` attribute of the parameter of the *consuming* call instruction, then `I` should be the `CallBase`, not `VInst`!
Let's re-read the patch:
```cpp
  if (const CallBase *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(VInst)) {
    FPClassTest NoFPClass = CB->getParamNoFPClass(U.getOperandNo());
    DemandedMask &= ~NoFPClass;
  }
```
If `I` is the consuming instruction, and it is a `CallBase`, then `I` should be cast to `CallBase`.
But the patch casts `VInst` to `CallBase`!
`VInst` is the *producing* instruction.
If `VInst` is a `CallBase`, it means the operand is a call.
Then it queries `CB->getParamNoFPClass(U.getOperandNo())`.
This is completely wrong! It queries the parameter attribute of the *producing* call, using the operand index of the *consuming* instruction!

Let's verify this.
If `I` is `fadd %a, %b` (operand 0 is `%a`, operand 1 is `%b`).
Suppose `%b` is `call float @foo(float %x, float %y)`.
Then `I` is `fadd`, `OpNo` is 1.
`V` is the `call float @foo`.
`VInst` is the `call float @foo`.
`CB` is the `call float @foo`.
`U.getOperandNo()` is 1.
It will query `CB->getParamNoFPClass(1)`, which is the `nofpclass` attribute of `%y` in `@foo`!
And it will apply this to the demanded mask of the result of `@foo`!
This is completely nonsensical! The `nofpclass` attribute of `@foo`'s argument `%y` has nothing to do with the demanded mask of `@foo`'s return value!

